<div id="review_399846747" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/399846747" />
    <a title="Elliott Turner" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5202972-elliott-turner"><img alt="Elliott Turner" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442516321p2/5202972.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/399846747?book_show_action=true">Aug 25, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elliott Turner" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elliott Turner" href="/user/show/5202972-elliott-turner">Elliott Turner</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer399846747" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7756659780092186565">This collection of stories is fantastic. It really does contain tales of love, craziness, and death. From the flirty young aristocracy of provincial &quot;Pampa&quot; Buenos Aires to the sweaty and gaucho-filled Northeast Argentina (near Paraguay), the tales hop, skip, and jump between class, location, and themes. A few of the dark stories bring to mind Flannery O&apos;Connor but with gauchos (cowboys). Some of the courting tales recall Joyce&apos;s best stories in Dubliners. I&apos;d lavish the book with five stars, bu</span>
  <span id="freeText7756659780092186565" style="display:none">This collection of stories is fantastic. It really does contain tales of love, craziness, and death. From the flirty young aristocracy of provincial "Pampa" Buenos Aires to the sweaty and gaucho-filled Northeast Argentina (near Paraguay), the tales hop, skip, and jump between class, location, and themes. A few of the dark stories bring to mind Flannery O'Connor but with gauchos (cowboys). Some of the courting tales recall Joyce's best stories in Dubliners. I'd lavish the book with five stars, but I couldn't stomach the handful of tales with animals as the protagonists. </span>
  <a data-text-id="7756659780092186565" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


